author: Vincent Theo
text: India has seen improvements in its economic growth. However, it is not "fast" by comparison. Sure, India's GDP growth rate is similar to China's. However, India's GDP in absolute terms is only about 20% of China, despite the similar population size. Hence, when the two countries both grow at around the same rate, the gap is actually widening rapidly. I am not taking anything away from India, but it should have leveraged its advantages much better.

author: milanrock Bhosale
text:
The combination of¬†protectionist,¬†import-substitution,¬†Fabian socialism, and¬†social democratic-inspired policies governed India for sometime after the end of British rule. The economy was then characterised by extensive regulation,¬†protectionism,¬†public ownership¬†of large monopolies, pervasive corruption and slow growth.[56][57][58]¬†Since 1991,¬†continuing economic liberalisation¬†has moved the country towards a¬†market-based economy.[56][57]¬†By 2008, India had established itself as one of the world's faster-growing economies.

Ancient and medieval eras

Indus Valley Civilisation

The citizens of the¬†Indus Valley Civilisation, a permanent settlement that flourished between 2800¬†BC and 1800¬†BC, practised agriculture, domesticated animals, used uniform weights and measures, made tools and weapons, and traded with other cities. Evidence of well-planned streets, a drainage system and¬†water supply¬†reveals their knowledge of¬†urban planning, which included the first-known urban¬†sanitation¬†systems and the existence of a form of municipal government.[59]

For a continuous duration of nearly 1700 years from the year 1 AD, India is the top most economy constituting 35 to 40% of world GDP.[60]

West Coast

Maritime trade was carried out extensively between¬†South India¬†and¬†Southeast¬†and West Asia from early times until around the fourteenth century AD. Both the¬†Malabar¬†and¬†Coromandel Coasts¬†were the sites of important trading centres from as early as the first century BC, used for import and export as well as transit points between the¬†Mediterranean¬†region and southeast Asia.[61]¬†Over time, traders organised themselves into associations which received state patronage. Historians Tapan Raychaudhuri and¬†Irfan Habibclaim this state patronage for overseas trade came to an end by the thirteenth century AD, when it was largely taken over by the local Parsi, Jewish, Syrian Christian and Muslim communities, initially on the Malabar and subsequently on the Coromandel coast.[62]

Silk Route

Other scholars suggest trading from India to West Asia and Eastern Europe was active between the 14th and 18th centuries.[63][64][65]¬†During this period, Indian traders settled in¬†Surakhani, a suburb of greater¬†Baku, Azerbaijan. These traders built a¬†Hindu temple, which suggests commerce was active and prosperous for Indians by the 17th century.[66][67][68][69]

Further north, the¬†Saurashtra¬†and¬†Bengal¬†coasts played an important role in maritime trade, and the¬†Gangetic plains¬†and the¬†Indus valley¬†housed several centres of river-borne commerce. Most overland trade was carried out via the¬†Khyber Passconnecting the¬†Punjab region¬†with Afghanistan and onward to the Middle East and Central Asia.[70]Although many kingdoms and rulers issued coins,¬†barter¬†was prevalent. Villages paid a portion of their agricultural produce as revenue to the rulers, while their craftsmen received a part of the crops at harvest time for their services.[71]

author: Melodic Nostalgic
text:
India is growing at ~8% Growth Rate per Year, And is currently a $3 Trillion Economy.. 

Assume :
A = Current Economy of India (In Trillion $), A = 3
Growth Rate, G = 8% per Year = 0.08 
Growth Rate Rise, R = 1% per Year = 0.01
Growth Rate Rise in 10 Years = 
  = A x (G+R) + A x (G+R).. So on till 10 Years..
  = 10 A (G + R)
  = 10 X 3 (8 + 1)
  = 30 (9)
  = 270 
 
Adding, A to Z, We get
A + (2.7 x A)
= 3 + (2.7 x 3)
= $ 11.1 Trillion Dollar Economy 

Indian Government recently announced  that it was aiming to make India a $10 Trillion Economy before 2028..  Although I'll be more pessimistic and say India will mostly likely be a $8 ~ $10 Trillion economy in next 10 Years, Because we assumed Growth Rate would go as high as 15%, Which may not be the case.

author: Donald Duck
text:
There are many problems with India but we seem to take peculiar pleasure in running down our country in front of foreigners

Yours truly travels a fair bit across the world, and has noticed a peculiar variety of Indian passport holder. The self-loathing Indian who takes it upon himself or herself to educate the world of India‚Äôs ills. This is rarely in front a group of Indians, but almost always when there are foreigners in the audience, the whiter they are the better.

Initially, I put up with this; heck, I will be the first to admit that I even joined in the conversation quite often but over the past decade I find these conversations not just irritating but positively anger-inducing.

This writer will be the first to admit that there are hundreds of systemic problems in India and then there are the historic wrongs that have been committed on a vast number of Indians some of which must be discussed at global forums. But much of the conversations I overhear nowadays are nothing but imagined wrongs or worse all driven by a unmitigated hatred of the party in power or more directly Prime Minister Narendra Modi.

The belief that badmouthing India is directly badmouthing the party in power or the man in power through complaining about India to a white audience befuddled me.

Not to stretch the ‚ÄòI met a taxi driver‚Äô analogy particularly favoured by self-loathing Indians but there have been Americans, Europeans and even Chinese folks I have met recently who after hearing such a conversation ask what is the problem with us Indians is and whether the Indian nation-state is on the verge of collapse.

Rightly did the great Hindi Poet Bhushana, who forsook the royal favours of the Mughal court to come over to Shivaji to record his glories, he sang :-‚Äú‡§ï‡§æ‡§∂‡•Ä ‡§ï‡•Ä ‡§ï‡§≤‡§æ ‡§ú‡§æ‡§§‡•Ä, ‡§Æ‡§•‡•Å‡§∞‡§æ ‡§ï‡•Ä ‡§Æ‡§∏‡§ú‡•Ä‡§¶ ‡§¨‡§®‡§§‡•Ä, ‡§Ö‡§ó‡§∞ ‡§∂‡§ø‡§µ‡§æ‡§ú‡•Ä ‡§®‡§æ ‡§π‡•ã‡§§‡•á ‡§§‡•ã ‡§∏‡§¨‡§ï‡•Ä ‡§∏‡•Å‡§®‡•ç‡§®‡§§ ‡§π‡•ã‡§§‡•Ä.‚Äù 
 meaning : (Had not there been Shivaji, Kashi would have lost its culture,Mathura would have been turned into a mosque and all would have been circumcised.)
If not for Shivaji and the Marathas, there would have existed a continuous Islamic belt from Morocco to Indonesia. What addition of 1 billion more adherents to Islam would have done to the world power balance or what would have happened to Indian legacy like yoga, ayurveda, music, art and philosophy, is not difficult to guess‚Ä¶.
It is worthwhile examining the 'what if' of Indias history, Aurengzeb, Akbars great great grandson, had embarked on the 'Islamisation' of India. The Marathas, inspired by Shivaji, fought Aurengzeb and saved India from following the fate of Persia. The proof of Maratha victory lies in the fact that Aurengzeb lies buried, not in Lahore /Delhi or Agra , but near Aurangabad in good old Maharashtra...
Indian history before Shivaji's advent reads like a chronicle of military disasters. Shivaji changed all that. He used Guerilla Tactics very effectively. Shivaji, as a great warrior & visionary laid a strong and solid foundation that after his death in 1680, there was a series of battles fought between Marathas and Mughals from 1681 to 1707 known as 'War of 27 years' and ended with the death of Aurangzeb in 1707. The Marathas eventually emerged victorious and consolidated their lost territories. This was further expanded by the Peshwas. The Maratha empire reached its peak in summer of 1758 with the conquest of Attock, which is banks of Indus river in Pakistan today. Its eastern frontier was today‚Äôs Orissa, being ruled by Raghuji Bhosale of Nagpur. Maratha armies had also reached upto Murshidabad, but then retreated and settled for tribute from Bengal and control of Orissa. To the south, in 1758, territories upto the fort of Gurramkonda in Kadappah district were held. Also, Tanjore (Thanjavur) was under Marathas, but that was a different line. In 1761, the PANIPAT war was lost to the Afghans but Marathas RECOVERED quickly like phoenix bird within 10 years and brought the whole of North Indian again under their control during the 1770's under leadership of Madhavrao Peshwa..
Eventually, the Marathas grew stronger and fought the British in three Anglo‚ÄìMaratha Wars (1775‚Äì82, 1803‚Äì05, 1817‚Äì18), In the First Anglo-Maratha War (1775‚Äì1782) The Marathas emerged Victorious. A Vijay Stambh (Victory Pillar) erected to commemorate Maratha victory over British is located at Vadgaon/Wadgaon Maval, close to the city of Pune. The 2nd and 3rd were subsequently lost and British established themselves.
(By the way, just for your G.K, Chatrapati Shivaji Maharaj is also  considered as the 'Father of the Indian Navy'.)

reply.author: putmyname ontheinternet?
reply.text: manufacturing and service sectors of indian economy are better off with a weaker currency. A weaker currency makes indain made goods more economically competitive, and it causes more jobs to be outsourced to india. So long as the domestic purchasing power of the rupee does not drop, we actually want the rupee to be weaker then other currencies. A country that does not itself rely on imports can have a strong domestic currency in terms of purchasing power/ average income while still having a weaker trading currency, making its products and services more competitive. This is ideal. It's also why china artificially undervalues its currency time and again.

author: John Johnson Jr.
text: For all Indians: Growth is almost just a natural consequence to just existing. That isn't something to be proud of by itself. The thing that sets modern economies apart is that they have coincidence of ideal workforce, technology, culture, and government aligned to maximize their growth potential. There are four things that will make India competitive and only three things: 1.) labor-force skilled to internationally competitive standards; 2.) culture that promotes all people to maximize economic participation (all genders and religions and races encouraged to learn, earn, and invest); 3.) state-of-the-art technology employed by industry; 4.) government that is capable of designing and organizing all the nation's human and material resources into an optimally productive and innovative economy. Since India is a Republic, all Indians need to learn to be cognizant of these four requirements and to be single-minded about achieving them. India will not be competitive and able to hold our own against China, Japan, Europe without these things. Without them, India will not enable all Indian children access to the quality of life their counterparts abroad can anticipate. Everything else is window-dressing in comparison.

author: anirban bhattacharya
text:
Why people focus so much on GDP growth i do not know.India's GDP growth looks great because of the size of the economy.In real terms it's as negligible as some country in West Africa.India manufactures a lot of small goods and exports them true.Indian textile and handicraft products are in high demand across the world that is also true.
But how many of you can see the effect tell me?Does the common man's life change?Does he get better education better health or better services? Nothing...
Regarding Artificial intelligence India is fast becoming a client nation instead of being an exporter or manager of AI.Flipkart which had the potential to become India's Amazon or a leader in big data analytics has already been purchased by Walmart.
Shouting Bharat mata ki jai at the top of your voice doesn't achieve anything or Allah hu akbar or any religious chant which are politicised in India would achieve anything.
Reasons for my pessimistic approach is simple.Indians are way too obsessed with themselves and are too selfish to look beyond their personal well being.And how can they?
Indians are a race of slaves who till only 70 years ago knew nothing but slavery.Every public institution every pillar of governance has been installed by a foreign power for our use.Indians own nothing.Hell even the system of governance is foreign designed.
Whatever little voice of reason there is in India gets suppressed in the loud din of savage demagogues.Whatever improvement there has been in India mostly happened thanks to the South Indian people.
I say all this from my experience as a public servant.
Being a superpower is a dream that might never materialise India actually risks becoming a colony of China in the decades to come.

author: coolgyani
text: Firstly, CNBC has shot some parts of it in Singapore as most folks have already pointed out. So it is not a true representation of India. Secondly, I have my complaints against the biased and banal imagery used in this video.  Why show India always as a bunch of snake charmers, hermits, temple goers, poor and uneducated bunch? This is a very biased view.  India is a growing country - it has pockets that have developed quite well and pockets that have not. The Western media is always focused on the latter. How is that a true representation? When you are talking about India 's growth why not show scenes of some of its growth engines such as software technology parks, special economic zones, its plethora of startups in glistening office spaces, its army of knowledge workers, traders on the floor of Bombay Stock Exchange and central business districts of some of the cities? There is poverty in India, no doubt. But it is also at a record low. There is a burgeoning middle class that is amongst the largest in the world. Show India in all its diversity and show India for what it is and what it can be.

author: Shiva Badruswamy
text: One thing not described here is the internal state-wise differences in India. India will never grow uniformly because Indian states have diverse economic agenda and social policies that puts different states at different levels. For instance, a state like Uttar Pradesh will NOT gain from India‚Äôs growth simply because of the low illiteracy rate leading to a HDI trap where the vicious cycle keeps the state in low HDI for a long time. Again there are large states in India like Kerala and TamilNadu where TFR has fallen to levels in some advanced nations. So these states would need Uttar Pradesh‚Äôs labor but the low HDI trap men‚Äôs these states are not going to get decent skilled labor from there. Countries like China and the US have these issues only to a minor extent. Indian statistics cannot be reported at the country level. Many western channels just do not understand that there are sub markets within India that are advanced and other sub markets like UP, Bihar, Jharkhand, Odisha etc.  in the vicious sub-Saharan African levels of HDI, low investment, high illiteracy, massive violence, heavy religious bent and exploitation,. So, overall India is a combination of sub Saharan type countries and mid to medium advanced nations in the world. And just like in the rest of the world, where people in low HDI trap countries migrate in search of better economic opportunities and health outcomes, so do the trends in India as well where people from sub-Saharan level economies migrate to relatively advanced economies in the country. India is a world in itself and that is how it will be for a long long time. You just can not describe India in a 5 minute clip - can you describe the world in 5 minutes? No. That‚Äôs what India is, a planet in itself, with all the complexities across the world present in 1 country.

author: Ajeet Albert
text: I do not support the idea of population being a problem with India. In fact, I contradict the educated modern people who blatantly shout overpopulation as the root cause. Unlike the West, Indians do not protest for minimum wage. Indians don't raise their voices for comforts or even basic needs. The Indian attitude is to work without complaining. The population which we criticize is the same population which has energy and will to work 24*7. They only need jobs. If the govt cannot provide jobs, we can't blame the people for existing. Focus on the next generation and offer education to improve their standards of life! The high rates of maternal and infant mortality is not because of people's mistake but rather it is the mistake of the govt is offer quality healthcare. 1in 5 children has nutritional deficiency. Malnutrition can be attributed to poverty but most nutritional deficiencies are due to unethical agricultural practices. The latter is the government's responsibility. Statistically, the number of genetic defects directly caused to children born around industrial areas is rising day by day. The disease burden, directly due to occupational contact as well as indirectly due to exposure from toxic wastes in air and water, are tremendously high. A healthy high population is an investment but we are complaining about it. Instead, the government is increasing the burden of unhealthy population yet we think it's all about development. Stop blaming the population and the people!! I feel pathetic for the millennial generation. Their whole world news comes from social media but they want to be blind towards ground reality in their own place. It's all about pointless stupid things like swach bharat,make in India etc etc.. We don't need reduction but rather we need stability.

reply.author: lucky
reply.text:
Joseph James Two important changes were made in calculation of GDP.
It has no miscalculation or something it was just correct to do that you can even see the parliament briefing of this 

1.The base year used for calculating the GDP is Shifted from 2004-05 to 2011-12. Base years will be changed, once they think that it has become irrelevant. Suppose India‚Äôs GDP is Rs. 100 and base year is 2000. Now, in 2015, many sectors such as IT, e-commerce, mobile telephony etc contributes to our economy, which were not present in 2000. Thus, India might be showing wrong GDP figures, since majority of economic activities driving sectors are not represented in Rs. 100. So, our govt. decides to change the base year.

2.Formerly, GDP is the total value of goods and services produced within the country during a year. Now, you take all final finished goods and services produced domestically in volume terms and multiply this by their market prices to arrive at the value of output. The value of output is the new GDP. In this new calculation since the value of goods and services taken at the market value to the formerly method at production value. The new GDP includes the taxes after deducting the subsidies by the government. The a reason for that being the way is, it is a global practice and this is more in line with other nations.
